  is a behavioral architecture problem. That's what we built.
</p>

<h2>The meta-point</h2>

<p>
  a16z's analysis validates a thesis we've held since the beginning: the deployment gap in
  physical AI is not primarily a perception problem, a manipulation problem, or a compute
  problem. It's a <strong>behavioral infrastructure problem</strong>. The robots can see.
  They can grasp. They can plan. What they can't do is monitor their own behavioral drift,
  enforce deterministic safety constraints independent of their learned policy, generate
  auditable compliance artifacts, and continuously improve their reliability through
  structured feedback loops.
</p>

<p>
  That's the layer we built. Not a better model. Not better hardware. A behavioral
  intelligence layer that makes any model production-deployable, any deployment insurable,
  and any improvement auditable.
</p>

